</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[590,683,1963,1989]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype, ♂ (ZFMK-TRI000830). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1102,1123,1962,1988]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A</emphasis>
. Dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1299,1319,1963,1989]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">B</emphasis>
. Drawing of a forewing. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[395,416,1998,2024]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">C</emphasis>
. Head in dorsal view, with scapus, compound eye and maxillary palp. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1233,1254,1998,2024]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">D</emphasis>
. Left maxillary palp. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[292,312,2033,2059]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">E</emphasis>
. Drawing of a maxillary palp. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[673,691,2033,2059]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">F</emphasis>
. Male genitalia in ventral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1070,1093,2033,2059]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">G</emphasis>
. Drawing of male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1314,303,333]" box="[227,1314,303,333]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,1314,303,333]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,566,303,333]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Key of males of species of</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Wichard, Neumann, Muller &amp; Wang, 2018" authorityName="Wichard, Neumann, Muller &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2018" box="[573,1314,303,333]" class="Insecta" family="Dysoneuridae" genus="Cretapsyche" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
Cretapsyche 
<bibRefCitation author="Wichard W. &amp; Neumann C. &amp; Muller P. &amp; Wang B." box="[751,1314,303,332]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="138 - 146" refId="ref3595" refString="Wichard W., Neumann C., Muller P. &amp; Wang B. 2018. Family Dysoneuridae (Insecta, Trichoptera) in Cretaceous Burmese amber. Cretaceous Research 82: 138 - 146. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2017.10.008" type="journal article" year="2018">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[751,1314,303,332]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Wichard, Neumann, Müller &amp; Wang, 2018</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1436,357,456]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Family and genus characters: five-segmented maxillary palps with second segment longest; threesegmented labial palps; forewing forks II, III, and V and hindwing forks I, III, and V present; tibial spurs 2/2/4.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1437,496,703]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
1. Forewing with Rs branching before M; in male genitalia, harpago shorter than coxopodite, coneshaped .................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Wichard &amp; Espeland, 2022" authorityName="Wichard &amp; Espeland" authorityYear="2022" box="[1092,1338,531,558]" class="Insecta" family="Dysoneuridae" genus="Cretapsyche" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kachini" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1092,1338,531,558]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Cretapsyche kachini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1346,1437,533,559]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1437,496,703]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">– Forewing with Rs and M branching at about same level; in male genitalia, harpago about as long as coxopodite.......................................................................................................................................... 2</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1437,496,703]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">– Forewing with M branching before Rs; in male genitalia, harpago shorter than coxopodite, needleshaped ................................................................................................................................................ 3</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1437,743,878]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
2. Labial palps with third segment oval, flattened; maxillary palps each with pilifer arising from third segment ............................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Wichard &amp; Neumann, 2019" authorityName="Wichard &amp; Neumann" authorityYear="2019" box="[830,1437,779,806]" class="Insecta" family="Dysoneuridae" genus="Cretapsyche" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palpinova">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[830,1104,779,806]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Cretapsyche palpinova</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wichard W. &amp; Neumann C." box="[1112,1437,779,806]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="51 - 56" refId="ref3549" refString="Wichard W. &amp; Neumann C. 2019. A new bizarre dysoneurid species (Insecta, Trichoptera) in Burmese amber. Fossil Record 22: 51 - 56. https: // doi. org / 10.5194 / fr- 22 - 51 - 2019" type="journal article" year="2019">Wichard &amp; Neumann, 2019</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
– Labial palps with third segment simple; maxillary palps simple, without pilifers.............................. ....................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Wichard, Neumann, Muller &amp; Wang, 2018" authorityName="Wichard, Neumann, Muller &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2018" box="[688,1437,851,878]" class="Insecta" family="Dysoneuridae" genus="Cretapsyche" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="circula">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[688,928,851,878]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Cretapsyche circula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wichard W. &amp; Neumann C. &amp; Muller P. &amp; Wang B." box="[935,1437,851,878]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="138 - 146" refId="ref3595" refString="Wichard W., Neumann C., Muller P. &amp; Wang B. 2018. Family Dysoneuridae (Insecta, Trichoptera) in Cretaceous Burmese amber. Cretaceous Research 82: 138 - 146. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2017.10.008" type="journal article" year="2018">Wichard, Neumann, Müller &amp; Wang, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1437,917,980]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
3. Forewing with thyridial cell open, fork V petiolate ........................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Wichard &amp; Espeland, 2022" authorityName="Wichard &amp; Espeland" authorityYear="2022" box="[1059,1339,917,944]" class="Insecta" family="Dysoneuridae" genus="Cretapsyche" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myanmari" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1059,1339,917,944]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Cretapsyche myanmari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1346,1437,918,944]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
– Forewing with thyridial cell closed, fork V nearly sessile................................................................. 4
</paragraph>
